{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":15812,"record_hash":"sha256:c9a8a321a91593ecb1fed1683a099a208e49a1ea85e2c1453aa20b73b57757db","timestamp":"2026-05-09T18:30:00.341Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"`TranscriptRecord` is the in-memory parsed record. It is what the transcript parser produces from a raw Codex/Claude JSONL line.\n\nSee [transcript.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/transcript.rs:94). It keeps parser-side facts: record index, raw-record hash, timestamp, provider event kind, extracted role/content/tool, and the original parsed JSON value.\n\n`TranscriptEnvelope` is the stored GitMeta shape. It is created right before writing to GitMeta.\n\nSee [gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:80). It adds storage context like `schema` and `source_key`, renames `index` to `record_index`, maps `source_record_hash` to `record_hash`, and redacts copied fields plus `source_record`.\n\nSo the flow is:\n\n```text\nraw JSONL line\n  -> TranscriptRecord      parser/intermediate representation\n  -> TranscriptEnvelope    redacted persistent GitMeta representation\n  -> JSON string in :transcript list\n```\n\nThe distinction is reasonable: `TranscriptRecord` belongs to parsing; `TranscriptEnvelope` belongs to storage. If they start looking identical after more pruning, then we can collapse them, but right now the redaction/storage boundary makes the split useful.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T18:30:00.341Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}